# <%ModuleName%>

<%Description%>

## Quick start

```powershell
git clone <your-repo-url>
cd <%ModuleName%>
./build/bootstrap.ps1
Invoke-Build -File ./build/module.build.ps1
```

## Project layout

```
<%ModuleName%>/
├── src/<%ModuleName%>/        Module source
│   ├── <%ModuleName%>.psd1    Manifest (runtime deps only)
│   ├── <%ModuleName%>.psm1    Entry point
│   ├── Public/                Exported functions
│   └── Private/               Internal helpers
├── build/
│   ├── module.build.ps1       InvokeBuild task graph
│   ├── bootstrap.ps1          Dependency installer
│   └── build.requires.psd1    Pinned tool versions (ModuleFast)
├── tests/
│   ├── unit/                  Pester 5 unit tests
│   └── integration/           Post-build artifact tests
└── docs/                      Generated help (platyPS)
```

## Build tasks

| Task              | Description                                            |
|-------------------|--------------------------------------------------------|
| `.` (default)     | Clean → Validate → Lint → Test → Docs → Package       |
| `Lint`            | PSScriptAnalyzer with project settings                 |
| `Test`            | Pester 5 unit tests + code coverage                    |
| `IntegrationTest` | Post-build artifact validation                         |
| `Docs`            | platyPS markdown and XML help generation               |
| `Package`         | Stage module + create archive                          |
| `Release`         | Full pipeline + publish to PSGallery                   |

## Adding a command

1. Create `src/<%ModuleName%>/Public/Verb-Noun.ps1`
2. Add the function name to `FunctionsToExport` in the manifest
3. Create `tests/unit/Public/Verb-Noun.Tests.ps1`
4. Run `Invoke-Build -File ./build/module.build.ps1 -Task Lint, Test`

If you have Anvil installed, you can use `New-AnvilFunction` to generate both files:

```powershell
New-AnvilFunction -FunctionName 'Verb-Noun' -Scope Public
```

## Renaming the module

To rename the module from `<%ModuleName%>` to a new name, update the following
locations. Work through them in order -- update file contents first, then rename
files and directories from deepest to shallowest.

**Before you start:** commit any pending changes so you can revert if needed.

### 1. File contents

Replace every occurrence of the old module name in these files:

| File | What to change |
|------|---------------|
| `build/build.settings.psd1` | `ModuleName = '<%ModuleName%>'` |
| `src/<%ModuleName%>/<%ModuleName%>.psd1` | `RootModule = '<%ModuleName%>.psm1'` and any other references |
| `tests/unit/<%ModuleName%>.Module.Tests.ps1` | `$ModuleName = '<%ModuleName%>'` and `Get-Module -Name '<%ModuleName%>'` |
| `tests/unit/Public/*.Tests.ps1` | `$ModuleName = '<%ModuleName%>'` and `Get-Module '<%ModuleName%>'` |
| `tests/unit/Private/*.Tests.ps1` | `$ModuleName = '<%ModuleName%>'`, `Get-Module '<%ModuleName%>'`, and `InModuleScope '<%ModuleName%>'` |
| `README.md` | Project title and any references |

A global find-and-replace across the project works well here. The module name
appears as a literal string (in quotes or as a path segment), so a plain text
search is sufficient.

### 2. File renames

```
src/<%ModuleName%>/<%ModuleName%>.psd1  →  src/<%ModuleName%>/NewName.psd1
src/<%ModuleName%>/<%ModuleName%>.psm1  →  src/<%ModuleName%>/NewName.psm1
tests/unit/<%ModuleName%>.Module.Tests.ps1  →  tests/unit/NewName.Module.Tests.ps1
```

### 3. Directory rename

```
src/<%ModuleName%>/  →  src/NewName/
```

Rename the directory last. All file contents and filenames already reference the
new name at this point.

### 4. Verify

```powershell
Invoke-Build -File ./build/module.build.ps1 -Task Lint, Test
```

If everything passes, commit the rename as a single commit so it is easy to
review or revert.

